# ⚠️ When NOT to Use HOC (Important in Interviews)

❌ Deep nesting → **wrapper hell**  
❌ Hard to debug props  
❌ Hooks often better now

✅ Prefer **Hooks** for:

*   State sharing
*   Data fetching
*   Logic reuse

***

# ✅ HOC vs Hooks (Say This in Interviews)

| Use Case               | Preferred |
| ---------------------- | --------- |
| Cross‑cutting behavior | ✅ HOC     |
| Local reusable logic   | ✅ Hooks   |
| Codebase consistency   | ✅ HOC     |
| New development        | Hooks     |
| Legacy systems         | ✅ HOC     |

***

# 🧠 Interview‑Ready 30‑Second Answer

> In real projects, HOCs are commonly used for cross‑cutting concerns such as authentication, role‑based access, error handling, loading indicators, analytics tracking, and feature flags. They help apply shared behavior across multiple components without duplicating logic, especially in large enterprise React applications.

***

# ✅ One‑Line Power Statement

> **HOCs are best for enforcing behavior across many components in large codebases.**

